{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"487b0d1c-a4a9-4de6-98fe-efbf80215a78","content":"In modern MSTest (v3+), you inject `TestContext` via the **constructor** and use `[TestInitialize]` for async setup. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IDisposable\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Constructor: synchronous init + TestContext injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here (e.g., create mocks, config)\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization (runs before each test)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        var result = await _service.DoWorkAsync();\n        Assert.IsNotNull(result);\n    }\n\n    // Cleanup (sync teardown via IDisposable)\n    public void Dispose()\n    {\n        _service?.Dispose();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** — MSTest 3.x injects `TestContext` as a constructor parameter (the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property still works but constructor injection is preferred).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports `async Task` for async setup; runs before each `[TestMethod]`.\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** — use for one-time async setup shared across all tests (must be `static`).\n- **`IDisposable` / `IAsyncDisposable`** — preferred over `[TestCleanup]` for deterministic teardown.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"85abd9bd-8a47-45c0-b894-c5c7cde547e3","outputTokens":427,"requestId":"800B:5D117:1642D1A:17A797D:6A0460FF"},"id":"746f2cdb-5468-4f2b-8139-e98ae386da7d","timestamp":"2026-05-13T11:31:22.686Z","parentId":"40e4a17f-67e9-47f0-b6ea-1ae73c35035a"}
